Implement CPU metrics collection for worker telemetry, reading from /proc/stat and calculating utilization percentages for monitoring worker load.

## Background and Justification
CPU utilization is the primary indicator of worker busyness. The benchmark scheduler uses this to:
- Determine if a worker is idle enough for benchmarking
- Inform the "balanced" selection strategy
- Display worker health in the dashboard

## Implementation Details

### Data Sources (Linux)
```rust
// Read from /proc/stat
// Format: cpu user nice system idle iowait irq softirq steal guest guest_nice
// cpu  10132153 290696 3084719 46828483 16683 0 25195 0 0 0

pub struct CpuStats {
    pub user: u64,
    pub nice: u64,
    pub system: u64,
    pub idle: u64,
    pub iowait: u64,
    pub irq: u64,
    pub softirq: u64,
    pub steal: u64,
    pub guest: u64,
    pub guest_nice: u64,
}

impl CpuStats {
    pub fn read_from_proc() -> Result<Self> {
        let content = std::fs::read_to_string("/proc/stat")?;
        Self::parse(&content)
    }

    pub fn parse(content: &str) -> Result<Self> {
        // Parse first line starting with "cpu "
    }

    pub fn total(&self) -> u64 {
        self.user + self.nice + self.system + self.idle + 
        self.iowait + self.irq + self.softirq + self.steal
    }

    pub fn active(&self) -> u64 {
        self.total() - self.idle - self.iowait
    }
}
```

### CPU Percentage Calculation
```rust
pub fn calculate_cpu_percent(prev: &CpuStats, curr: &CpuStats) -> f64 {
    let total_delta = curr.total().saturating_sub(prev.total());
    let active_delta = curr.active().saturating_sub(prev.active());

    if total_delta == 0 {
        return 0.0;  // No time passed
    }

    (active_delta as f64 / total_delta as f64) * 100.0
}
```

